<br>
Yes I know people sometimes do it from fan art, and yes I have drawn things from reference since i was in Kindergarten. But where is the &quot;art&quot; in that? Its like trying to copy someone's lifestyle or being a poser, it just isn't yourself. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upuhfyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Puhfyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/29/01 8:08:45 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Don't flame me but..</span><hr size=1> the reason i love anime is because you can start with a blank piece of paper and then draw whatever you want, you dont need a model or anything, its all imagination<br>
<br>
i agree, but using a reference pic or copying helps developing artists to build skills and to master proportions... i will have to download pics of anime hands and redraw them in different poses, cause right now im horrible at hands<br>
<br>
i think that drawing 'fan art' is beneficial to see how characters are designed and provide a good reference, however i think that fan art should be a very small portion of an artists art<br>
<br>
drawing gives you the ability to draw whatever you can think of to draw, which is really cool.... you can draw things you cant experinece in reality... i dont understand why people just do fanart or copy trace... but its good for reference <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/udarkreaver66.showPublicProfile?language=EN>darkreaver66</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/29/01 8:42:49 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/avatar2.jpg width=64 height=64></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: </span><hr size=1> It's interesting...this argument surfaced not too long ago, except it was much more violent and heated.<br>
<br>
...do you really think that copying is degrading to the arts?  I'm not so convinced.  Look at chuck close's work...the photorealisitc stuff.  His paintings literally look like photographs...all the little pores in the skin, blemishes, hair follicles.  You can't say that that took no skill...on the contrary.  And very likely he based the paintings closely on photographs....references...copying them exactly, no less.  There are in fact members of this board who take references and copy them astoundingly closely...and that skill indeed is an art.<br>
<br>
I think it might be a good idea to to see art from a different point of view...accept a broader interpretation of art.<br>
<br>
But then again, that doesn't mean I find that sort of stuff appealing...but I can easily accept copying references as art.<br>
