<br>
Now... people say they use them as a learning tool, it helps them with proportions anatomy, blah blah blah. I don't agree completely, but they can do what they want. I say if you want to learn anatomy and proportion, look at a person, not a drawing of a person. Learn from the source, not a middle man. You're just copying someone else's interpretation of what a human (or whatever you're copying) should look like. That artist made every decision for you, you're copying their art and their style. I don't consider it that helpful. Looking at something to get a pose, while not copying it line for line, is a little different. Of course it should be given credit, but it's not as bad as just laying down lines the exact same.<br>
<br>
And please... there is nothing wrong with fan art, but people have polluted the term. Fan art is not copying a picture, that's just copying. Fan art is ORIGINAL art based on EXISTING characters or ideas. It isn't copying a picture, it's using things that you didn't come up with, that you're a FAN of, and drawing it yourself. I guess you can consider copying fan art, but let's call it what it really is, so that we can retain what the term actually means. <p><table width=100% border=0>
