<br>
I copy a LOT of stuff when I'm trying to learn how to do accomplish something. Anatomy and proportions are the easiest thing to learn from people or other animals by drawing life. I PREFER to not use reference if I don't need to, but I don't look down on people that do. I still don't think that copying stylized works is the best way to learn, at least not as your ONLY means of learning. Again, that's just me. These are all opinions, and no one has to agree.<br>
<br>
Do I think you can't be creative when copying pictures? Of course. Trust me, it gets on my nerves just as much as yours when people are put down (and I've seen it done on this board) for using photo reference. Telling them that they aren't being creative, that they are somehow lesser of an artist. It would be ridiculous for me to sit here and insult anyone for doing it considering I've been using photos constantly for all my art projects lately that required me to draw a person. I don't see how it's any different than drawing from real life (besides the fact that your subject won't move).<br>
<br>
I do realize I said that it inhibits your creativity to rely on photographs too much, and I still think it does sometimes. I think the best way to use photographs is to take them yourself, so at least that way you get to determine the positionings and content. That doesn't mean it's wrong to use photographs, whether you take them yourself or not, and even if I or anyone else thought it was: so what? You say you do it for yourself, then who cares what other people think? We shouldn't even be a factor.<br>
<br>
And just because I don't think it's the best way to learn or whatever, that doesn't mean I factor that into my critique (if I were to critique). I don't sit there and lecture the person on what they should be doing, I don't tell them I'm right and their way is wrong, they can do whatever they want. I just do what I'm supposed to do, critique. Obviously you can reference creatively. Like you said, you alter the photo instead of making it an exact duplication. Obviously, that's creative. And same thing with the masters. I mean, they didn't just randomly place people in their paintings. They used models, but they also placed them creatively, and put them into surroundings that they weren't in previously. Just because they used models doesn't mean they aren't creative, just like people that use photos aren't inherintly not creative. <p><table width=100% border=0>
