<br>
No.  You didn't mean it to be a flame, but it comes up over and over and over again and no not all the great works of art are innovative in that the image has been changed, rather in the way the paint was applied, or the type of medium used, the colors that are used, the composition, etc.  Creativity does not begin and end with altering your reference.  I believe it was da Vinci (and I could be wrong about who) that has been noted for his ability to reproduce what he saw and give it a 3D quality.  What was most valued in certain works was that no matter how close nor how far you were from the work ... the image still maintained the desired dimensional effect.  This is a skill that not many artists are able to master.  It is very difficult to produce something on a large scale and have the detailing look as good and has as much dimension from both near and far.  This is something that I am able to do.  This is something that I worked very hard to master.  My drawings don't just have a photo realistic quality to them, they have dimension.  <br>
<br>
